{"id":499,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":499,"title":"Fig tree","subtitle":"","short_title":"Fig tree","uri":"/scriptures/bd/fig-tree","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/fig-tree.t1","order":".000.1300"},[".title","Fig tree"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/fig-tree.p1","order":".000.1301"},"Everywhere common in Palestine, both wild and cultivated. Figs were an important food. The tree is one of the earliest to show its fruitbuds, which appear before the leaves; thus a fig tree with leaves would be expected to also have fruit. Jesus’ cursing the fig tree for its fruitlessness (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/mark/11.12-13,20-23"},"Mark 11:12–13, 20–23"],") was an allusion to the fruitlessness of Israel. The time when the leaves appear indicates that summer is “nigh at hand” (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/matt/24.32-33"},"Matt. 24:32–33"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/45.37-38"},"D&C 45:37–38"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/pgp/js-m/1.38-39"},"JS—M 1:38–39"],"). For other references to figs, see",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/3.7"},"Gen. 3:7"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/4.25"},"1 Kgs. 4:25"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/20.7"},"2 Kgs. 20:7"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/john/1.47-50"},"John 1:47–50"],". The sycomore, spoken of in",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/isa/9.10"},"Isa. 9:10"],",",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/amos/7.14"},"Amos 7:14"],", and",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/luke/19.4"},"Luke 19:4"],", was a variety of fig tree."]]],"refs":null}
